<p>
Quite often in Emacs, especially when writing Clojure code, I want to
reindent the entire file. I think that arises from the fact that I'm
writing a lot of Lisp these days, and Lisp is the only language I've
ever encountered where automatic indenting actually works well.
</p>

<p>
Anyway, here's the code I use to map <code>meta-shift-q</code> to "reindent the
whole buffer":
</p>

<div class="org-src-container">

<pre class="src src-emacs-lisp">(<span style="color: #66D9EF;">defun</span> <span style="color: #F92672; font-style: italic;">reindent-whole-buffer</span> ()
  <span style="color: #E6DB74; font-style: italic;">"Reindent the whole buffer."</span>
  (interactive)
  (indent-region (point-min)
                 (point-max)))

(global-set-key (kbd <span style="color: #E6DB74;">"M-Q"</span>) 'reindent-whole-buffer)
</pre>
</div>

<p>
Pretty simple, huh?
</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/KrisJenkinsBlog/~4/QPg2kI1QWDw" height="1" width="1"/>